k, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Greenleafe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Essex and Middlesex): from Middle English <i>grene</i> ‘green’ + <i>lef</i> ‘leaf’, presumably applied as a nickname, the significance of which is now lost.","Jewish (American): translation into English of the Ashkenazic artificial surname <b>Grünblatt</b>, a compound of German <i>grün</i> + <i>Blatt</i> ‘leaf’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French Canadian   Vertefeuille  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Greenlief","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English or Jewish   Greenleaf  ."]},{"name":"Vertefeuille","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emilien, Laurent.","French Canadian: soldier's name from French <i>verte feuille</i> ‘green leaf’. Compare   Greenleaf  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Nicolas Bachand <i>dit</i> Vertefeuille from France (see   Bachand  ). His descendants also bear an altered (translated) form of the <i>dit</i> name, <i>Greenleaf</i>."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Rose Greenleafe was born about 1510, in Holbrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Greenleafe, was 41 and her mother, Agnes Yaxley, was 39. She married John Everard in 1534, in Runton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 10 January 1567, in Holbrook, Suffolk, England, at the age of 58, and was buried in Auckland St Andrew, Durham, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1510–10 January 1567":"umbes 1510–10. jaanuar 1567","1510–1567":"1510–1567","1516–Female":"1516–Surnud","1510–1572":"1510–1572","1535–1613":"1535–1613","1471–Male":"1471–Surnud","1473–1532":"1473–1532","10 January 1567":"10. jaanuar 1567","1473":"1473","1572":"1572","21 November 1535":"21. november 1535","1471":"1471","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1535":"1535","1534":"1534","1567":"1567","1532":"1532","1510":"1510"